      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>I have visited France three times in the last year and find the reported chill in French-American relations greatly exaggerated. ''Wheels of Fortune,'' by Geoffrey Wheatcroft (Op-Ed, July 24), about Lance Armstrong, is the latest take on this non-story.</p>
        <p>During a trip to France last week, I read about the Tour de France in several major newspapers and found nothing about Armstrong that was not courteous or fair. Nearly everything, in fact, was quite complimentary, both of Armstrong himself and the crack United States Postal Service team.</p>
        <p>I was delighted to witness the patrons of a cafe in Normandy applaud the Texan's victory in a stage of the Tour.</p>
        <p>Armstrong is gracious and humble to everyone, especially French journalists, whom he addresses in their native tongue. The French would certainly prefer one of their own, but Armstrong clearly has their respect.</p>
        <p>Jonathan Yaeger  New York, July 24, 2004</p>
      </block>
